This is actually a brilliant and highly underrated approach. By giving them a memorable, randomly generated "Sync Phrase" instead of asking for an email and password, you completely remove the onboarding friction while still allowing cross-device syncing.

This model is famously used by privacy-first companies like Mullvad VPN (where your account is just a random 16-digit number) and fits the German data privacy mindset perfectly.

Here is a breakdown of how you can structure this system effectively, keep it frictionless, and ensure it actually works for your users.

1. Naming: It's a "Sync Code," Not a Username
Don't call it a username. A "username" implies a public profile that others can see. Call it a "Sync Code" or "Recovery Phrase." To make it memorable but unique enough to avoid collisions, use the Adjective-Noun-Number format.

Bad (Hard to remember): user_894f2a

Good (Easy to remember): Clever-Panda-42 or Neon-Coffee-99

When the user opens the app for the first time, you automatically generate this code, save it to their browser (localStorage), and show them a tiny notification: "You are browsing anonymously as Clever-Panda-42. Save this name to sync your feed on other devices."

2. The 5-Second Onboarding (Getting their preferences)
Since your database holds the top 100 articles across multiple domains, you need to know which ones to push to the top of their feed. Do not make this a long survey. Make it a mandatory, one-time visual pop-up on their first visit.

The Flow:

Screen 1: "Welcome to DailyAI. What matters to you?"

Action: Show 8-10 large, tappable pill buttons with emojis (e.g., 💼 Business, 🧬 Health tech, 💻 Coding, 🤖 LLMs, ⚖️ AI Ethics).

Rule: "Pick at least 2 to build your feed."

Result: Once they tap two and hit "Start Reading," your database links those tags to Clever-Panda-42.

3. How the Filtering Logic Works
Here is how you connect their preferences to your Top 100 database:

The Database Setup: Every article in your Top 100 database needs to be tagged with one or more domains (e.g., Article A = LLMs, Business).

The User Profile: Clever-Panda-42's profile in your database simply looks like: {"tags": ["Business", "Coding"], "saved_articles": [id1, id2]}.

The Feed Generation: When Clever-Panda-42 opens the app, your server grabs the Top 100 list, pulls out the articles tagged with "Business" and "Coding," puts those at the very top of the stack, and leaves the rest underneath.

4. The Reality Check: The "Security" Trade-off
You need to be completely candid with yourself about the security of this method: It has zero security, and that is perfectly fine.

If someone accidentally types in Clever-Panda-42 on their phone, they will see someone else's saved AI news articles. Because you are not storing credit cards, private messages, or personal emails, this is an acceptable risk. However, you should never allow users to choose their own sync code (otherwise everyone will pick "Admin" or "Test" and overwrite each other's feeds). Always auto-generate it.

The Transition to Monetization Later
When you eventually decide to monetize (e.g., offering the premium audio briefings or the B2B deep dives we talked about), you simply add a button in the settings: "Claim this profile. Add an email to upgrade to DailyAI Pro." They keep their streak, their saved articles, and their preferences, but transition to a secure account.

